  "prompt": "How was Ankara chosen to be the capital of Turkey?",
  "response": "Ankara became the capital of Turkey in 1923 during the Turkish War of Independence, led by Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk. Several key factors influenced this decision:\n\n1. Strategic Location: Ankara is centrally located in Anatolia, making it more defensible and accessible compared to Istanbul, which was closer to the coast and more vulnerable to foreign invasion.\n\n2. Historical Significance: The region had historical importance and was a significant location during the Ankara War against the Greeks in the Turkish War of Independence.\n\n3. Distance from Ottoman Past: By moving the capital from Istanbul (the former Ottoman capital) to Ankara, Atat\u00fcrk symbolically broke from the imperial past and highlighted the new, modern Turkish Republic.\n\n4. Less Foreign Influence: Unlike cosmopolitan Istanbul, Ankara was less influenced by foreign powers and represented a more purely Turkish environment.\n\n5. Economic Potential: The city was seen as having potential for development and modernization, aligning with Atat\u00fcrk's vision of a progressive nation.\n\nBefore becoming the capital, Ankara was a small, relatively insignificant town. After being chosen, it underwent massive transformation and development to become the administrative center of the new Turkish Republic.\n\nThe decision was part of Atat\u00fcrk's broader reforms aimed at creating a modern, secular, and nationally focused Turkish state.",
